# Liquidation — Cursor Rules
# Paper-trading competition platform for crypto perpetual futures
# Stack: Next.js App Router, TypeScript, Tailwind CSS, shadcn/ui, Neon Postgres, Clerk

## Project Identity
- App name: Liquidation
- Purpose: Simulated crypto perpetuals trading competitions with real-time price data
- Design theme: Deep/Neon Blue trading terminal (Hyperliquid-inspired)
- Cost constraint: 100% free-tier APIs — never suggest paid endpoints

---

## Architecture Rules

### WebSocket (CRITICAL)
- The Binance WebSocket `wss://stream.binance.com:9443/ws/!ticker@arr` MUST only be
  used CLIENT-SIDE inside a `useEffect` hook in a `'use client'` component.
- NEVER call any WebSocket from a Server Component, Server Action, or API route.
  A server-side WebSocket would mean one IP hits Binance for all users and get banned.
- The custom hook for this is `useBinanceTicker` in `/hooks/useBinanceTicker.ts`.
  Always import live prices from this hook on the client.

### Server Actions vs Client
- Server Actions use the Binance REST endpoint for price fetches:
  `https://api.binance.com/api/v3/ticker/price?symbol=BTCUSDT`
- Client components use the `useBinanceTicker` WebSocket hook for live prices.
- Never mix these up. REST on server, WebSocket on client.

### Next.js App Router
- Use the App Router exclusively. No `pages/` directory.
- Co-locate Server Components and Client Components. Default to Server Components;
  add `'use client'` only when hooks, state, or browser APIs are needed.
- Use Server Actions (in `/actions/`) for all database mutations. No API routes
  unless absolutely necessary.
- Use `loading.tsx` and `error.tsx` in route segments.

