## Database And Auth Rules (Neon + Clerk)

### Schema Integrity
- Never modify the core tables (`users`, `rooms`, `room_participants`, `positions`)
  without updating the TypeScript types in `/lib/types.ts` at the same time.
- Use Clerk user IDs (`text`) for `users.id`; use `uuid` for room, participant,
  and position primary keys. Never use auto-increment integers.
- All timestamps are `timestamptz` (timezone-aware), not plain `timestamp`.

### Authorization
- Clerk is the source of truth for authentication. Use `@clerk/nextjs/server`
  in Server Components and Server Actions.
- Database authorization must be enforced server-side in every query or mutation.
  Users can only mutate their own participant rows and positions.
- Leaderboard queries may read all participants in the current room after the
  signed-in user is verified as a room participant.
- Never expose `DATABASE_URL` or `CLERK_SECRET_KEY` to client components.

### Queries
- Always use the lazy Neon SQL client from `/lib/db.ts`.
- Prefer explicit column lists over `select *` for performance and stable types.
- Cast Postgres `numeric` values to `float8` in SELECT queries when returning
  them to TypeScript UI code.
- Surface database errors with human-readable messages. Never silently swallow errors.

